[2026-03-13T18:27:02Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01YLnwH7wTkHAugTXJXK75xV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Y7jdSkxCLDamzvoGbCrjgY","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/cmd/cloche/help.go"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4917,"cache_read_input_tokens":45086,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4917,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01R6FyHX8ezBGpk4fQZXf4qj","session_id":"c0b250b2-f9c5-4d6e-a2b5-21933ebd9c8c","uuid":"b6209900-cf92-4a00-b156-9662fbfc7df8"}
[2026-03-13T18:27:02Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Y7jdSkxCLDamzvoGbCrjgY","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package main\n     2→\n     3→import (\n     4→\t\"fmt\"\n     5→\t\"os\"\n     6→)\n     7→\n     8→// subcommandHelp maps each subcommand to its detailed help text.\n     9→// Help text is formatted for LLM consumption: structured, explicit, with examples.\n    10→var subcommandHelp = map[string]string{\n    11→\t\"init\": `cloche init — Initialize a Cloche project\n    12→\n    13→Creates the .cloche/ directory with a workflow definition, Dockerfile,\n    14→prompt templates, and configuration files.\n    15→\n    16→Usage:\n    17→  cloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <image>]\n    18→\n    19→Flags:\n    20→  --workflow <name>       Name for the workflow file (default: \"develop\")\n    21→  --base-image <image>    Base Docker image for the Dockerfile (default: \"cloche-base:latest\")\n    22→\n    23→What it creates:\n    24→  .cloche/<name>.cloche           Workflow definition\n    25→  .cloche/host.cloche             Host orchestration workflow\n    26→  .cloche/Dockerfile              Container image definition\n    27→  .cloche/config.toml             Project configuration\n    28→  .cloche/prompts/implement.md    Prompt for the implement step\n    29→  .cloche/prompts/fix.md          Prompt for the fix step\n    30→  .cloche/prompts/update-docs.md  Prompt for the update-docs step\n    31→  .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh  Prompt generation script\n    32→  .cloche/version                 Schema version marker\n    33→\n    34→Existing files are never overwritten. Run this command again safely to add\n    35→missing files without losing customizations.\n    36→\n    37→Examples:\n    38→  cloche init\n    39→  cloche init --workflow build --base-image python:3.12\n    40→`,\n    41→\n    42→\t\"health\": `cloche health — Show project health summary\n    43→\n    44→Queries the daemon's HTTP API for a summary of all registered projects\n    45→and their pass/fail test counts.\n    46→\n    47→Usage:\n    48→  cloche health\n    49→\n    50→Environment:\n    51→  CLOCHE_HTTP    Daemon HTTP address (e.g. \"localhost:8080\"). Required.\n    52→\n    53→Examples:\n    54→  export CLOCHE_HTTP=localhost:8080\n    55→  cloche health\n    56→`,\n    57→\n    58→\t\"run\": `cloche run — Launch a workflow run\n    59→\n    60→Starts a new container workflow run. The daemon builds/pulls the container\n    61→image, copies the project into it, and executes the workflow steps.\n    62→\n    63→Usage:\n    64→  cloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n    65→  cloche run <name>              (shorthand: bare positional workflow name)\n    66→\n    67→Flags:\n    68→  --workflow <name>    Name of the workflow to run (required). Must match a\n    69→                       .cloche/<name>.cloche file in the project.\n    70→  --prompt \"...\"       Prompt text passed to agent steps. Also available as\n    71→  -p \"...\"             the short form.\n    72→  --title \"...\"        Human-readable title for the run (shown in status/list).\n    73→  --keep-container     Do not remove the container after the run completes.\n    74→                       Useful for debugging.\n    75→\n    76→The command prints the run ID on success. Use that ID with status, logs,\n    77→poll, and stop.\n    78→\n    79→Examples:\n    80→  cloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add a /health endpoint\"\n    81→  cloche run develop -p \"Fix the broken CSV parser\" --title \"CSV fix\"\n    82→  cloche run --workflow build --keep-container\n    83→`,\n    84→\n    85→\t\"status\": `cloche status — Check run status\n    86→\n    87→Shows the current state of a workflow run including its type, active step,\n    88→and the result of each completed step.\n    89→\n    90→Usage:\n    91→  cloche status <run-id>\n    92→\n    93→Arguments:\n    94→  <run-id>    The run identifier returned by \"cloche run\".\n    95→\n    96→Output fields:\n    97→  Run         Run identifier\n    98→  Title       Human-readable title (if set)\n    99→  Workflow    Workflow name\n   100→  Type        \"host\" or \"container\"\n   101→  State       Current state (e.g. running, succeeded, failed, cancelled)\n   102→  Container   Truncated container ID (container runs only)\n   103→  Error       Error message (if failed)\n   104→  Active      Name of the currently executing step\n   105→  Steps       List of completed steps with results and timestamps\n   106→\n   107→Examples:\n   108→  cloche status abc123\n   109→`,\n   110→\n   111→\t\"logs\": `cloche logs — Show logs for a run\n   112→\n   113→Streams or displays log output for a workflow run. Supports filtering by\n   114→step name and log type, and can follow live output.\n   115→\n   116→Usage:\n   117→  cloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [--follow]\n   118→\n   119→Arguments:\n   120→  <run-id>    The run identifier.\n   121→\n   122→Flags:\n   123→  --step <name>                  Show logs only for the named step.\n   124→  --type <full|script|llm>       Filter by log type:\n   125→                                   full    — complete unfiltered output\n   126→                                   script  — script/command output only\n   127→                                   llm     — LLM interaction logs only\n   128→  --follow, -f                   Stream logs in real time (blocks until the\n   129→                                 run completes or is stopped).\n   130→\n   131→Examples:\n   132→  cloche logs abc123\n   133→  cloche logs abc123 --step implement --type llm\n   134→  cloche logs abc123 -f\n   135→  cloche logs abc123 --step test --type script\n   136→`,\n   137→\n   138→\t\"poll\": `cloche poll — Wait for a run to finish\n   139→\n   140→Polls the daemon every 2 seconds and prints step-level progress until the\n   141→run reaches a terminal state (succeeded, failed, or cancelled).\n   142→\n   143→Usage:\n   144→  cloche poll <run-id>\n   145→\n   146→Arguments:\n   147→  <run-id>    The run identifier.\n   148→\n   149→Exit codes:\n   150→  0    Run succeeded.\n   151→  1    Run failed, was cancelled, or the container died.\n   152→\n   153→Examples:\n   154→  cloche poll abc123\n   155→  cloche run develop -p \"Fix bug\" && cloche poll \"$(cloche run develop -p 'Fix bug')\"\n   156→`,\n   157→\n   158→\t\"list\": `cloche list — List workflow runs\n   159→\n   160→Shows all runs for the current project, or all runs across all projects\n   161→with --all.\n   162→\n   163→Usage:\n   164→  cloche list [--all]\n   165→\n   166→Flags:\n   167→  --all    Show runs from all projects (default: current project only).\n   168→\n   169→Output columns: run ID, workflow name, state, type (host/container),\n   170→title, container ID, and error message (if any).\n   171→\n   172→Examples:\n   173→  cloche list\n   174→  cloche list --all\n   175→`,\n   176→\n   177→\t\"stop\": `cloche stop — Stop a running workflow\n   178→\n   179→Sends a stop signal to a running workflow. The container is terminated\n   180→and the run state transitions to \"cancelled\".\n   181→\n   182→Usage:\n   183→  cloche stop <run-id>\n   184→\n   185→Arguments:\n   186→  <run-id>    The run identifier.\n   187→\n   188→Examples:\n   189→  cloche stop abc123\n   190→`,\n   191→\n   192→\t\"delete\": `cloche delete — Delete a retained container\n   193→\n   194→Removes a container that was kept after a run (via --keep-container).\n   195→Accepts either a container ID or a run ID.\n   196→\n   197→Usage:\n   198→  cloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n   199→\n   200→Arguments:\n   201→  <container-or-run-id>    Container ID or run ID to delete.\n   202→\n   203→Examples:\n   204→  cloche delete abc123\n   205→`,\n   206→\n   207→\t\"tasks\": `cloche tasks — Show task pipeline and assignment state\n   208→\n   209→Queries the daemon's HTTP API for the current task list, showing which\n   210→tasks are open, assigned, or completed.\n   211→\n   212→Usage:\n   213→  cloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n   214→\n   215→Flags:\n   216→  --project <dir>    Project directory name to query (default: current\n   217→                     directory basename).\n   218→\n   219→Environment:\n   220→  CLOCHE_HTTP    Daemon HTTP address (default: \"localhost:8080\").\n   221→\n   222→Output columns: ID, STATUS, ASSIGNED, RUN, TITLE\n   223→\n   224→Examples:\n   225→  cloche tasks\n   226→  cloche tasks --project my-app\n   227→`,\n   228→\n   229→\t\"loop\": `cloche loop — Manage the orchestration loop\n   230→\n   231→Starts or stops the daemon's orchestration loop, which automatically\n   232→picks up and runs tasks from the task pipeline.\n   233→\n   234→Usage:\n   235→  cloche loop [--max <n>]     Start the orchestration loop\n   236→  cloche loop stop            Stop the orchestration loop\n   237→\n   238→Flags:\n   239→  --max <n>    Maximum number of concurrent runs (default: value from\n   240→               .cloche/config.toml).\n   241→\n   242→Examples:\n   243→  cloche loop\n   244→  cloche loop --max 3\n   245→  cloche loop stop\n   246→`,\n   247→\n   248→\t\"get\": `cloche get — Get a value from the run context store\n   249→\n   250→Reads a key from the run's context.json file. Intended for use inside\n   251→workflow scripts and steps.\n   252→\n   253→Usage:\n   254→  cloche get <key>\n   255→\n   256→Arguments:\n   257→  <key>    The context key to read.\n   258→\n   259→Environment:\n   260→  CLOCHE_RUN_ID        Run identifier (required).\n   261→  CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR   Project directory (default: current directory).\n   262→\n   263→Exit codes:\n   264→  0    Key exists; value printed to stdout.\n   265→  1    Key not found or error.\n   266→\n   267→Examples:\n   268→  cloche get branch\n   269→  cloche get task_id\n   270→`,\n   271→\n   272→\t\"set\": `cloche set — Set a value in the run context store\n   273→\n   274→Writes a key-value pair to the run's context.json file. Use \"-\" as the\n   275→value to read from stdin (useful for multi-line content).\n   276→\n   277→Usage:\n   278→  cloche set <key> <value>\n   279→  cloche set <key> -          (read value from stdin)\n   280→\n   281→Arguments:\n   282→  <key>      The context key to write.\n   283→  <value>    The value to store, or \"-\" to read from stdin.\n   284→\n   285→Environment:\n   286→  CLOCHE_RUN_ID        Run identifier (required).\n   287→  CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR   Project directory (default: current directory).\n   288→\n   289→Examples:\n   290→  cloche set branch feature-auth\n   291→  echo \"multi-line content\" | cloche set notes -\n   292→`,\n   293→\n   294→\t\"workflow\": `cloche workflow — View workflow definitions\n   295→\n   296→Lists all workflows in the project or renders a specific workflow as an\n   297→ASCII-art graph showing steps, wiring, and result paths.\n   298→\n   299→Usage:\n   300→  cloche workflow [--project <dir>]          List all workflows\n   301→  cloche workflow <name> [--project <dir>]   Show workflow graph\n   302→\n   303→Arguments:\n   304→  <name>    Name of the workflow to render as a graph.\n   305→\n   306→Flags:\n   307→  --project <dir>, -p <dir>    Project directory (default: current directory).\n   308→\n   309→When listing, workflows are grouped by type (container or host). When\n   310→showing a specific workflow, the output is a graph with step boxes and\n   311→colored wires: green for success, red for fail/failed, and\n   312→blue/yellow/orange/magenta for other result paths. Wires to the same\n   313→destination are merged for readability.\n   314→\n   315→Examples:\n   316→  cloche workflow\n   317→  cloche workflow develop\n   318→  cloche workflow main -p /path/to/project\n   319→  cloche workflow --project ../other-project\n   320→`,\n   321→\n   322→\t\"shutdown\": `cloche shutdown — Shut down the daemon\n   323→\n   324→Sends a shutdown signal to the Cloche daemon. All running workflows are\n   325→stopped and the daemon process exits.\n   326→\n   327→Usage:\n   328→  cloche shutdown\n   329→\n   330→Examples:\n   331→  cloche shutdown\n   332→`,\n   333→}\n   334→\n   335→// printHelp prints the top-level help or subcommand-specific help.\n   336→// Returns true if help was printed (caller should exit).\n   337→func printHelp(args []string) bool {\n   338→\tif len(args) == 0 {\n   339→\t\tprintTopLevelHelp()\n   340→\t\treturn true\n   341→\t}\n   342→\n   343→\t// \"cloche help <subcommand>\"\n   344→\tcmd := args[0]\n   345→\tif text, ok := subcommandHelp[cmd]; ok {\n   346→\t\tfmt.Fprint(os.Stderr, text)\n   347→\t\treturn true\n   348→\t}\n   349→\n   350→\tfmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \"unknown command: %s\\n\\n\", cmd)\n   351→\tprintTopLevelHelp()\n   352→\treturn true\n   353→}\n   354→\n   355→// hasHelpFlag returns true if the args contain --help or -h.\n   356→func hasHelpFlag(args []string) bool {\n   357→\tfor _, arg := range args {\n   358→\t\tif arg == \"--help\" || arg == \"-h\" {\n   359→\t\t\treturn true\n   360→\t\t}\n   361→\t}\n   362→\treturn false\n   363→}\n   364→\n   365→// printSubcommandHelp prints help for a subcommand and exits.\n   366→func printSubcommandHelp(cmd string) {\n   367→\tif text, ok := subcommandHelp[cmd]; ok {\n   368→\t\tfmt.Fprint(os.Stderr, text)\n   369→\t} else {\n   370→\t\tfmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \"no help available for %q\\n\", cmd)\n   371→\t}\n   372→}\n   373→\n   374→func printTopLevelHelp() {\n   375→\tfmt.Fprint(os.Stderr, `cloche — Grow-code high quality applications\n   376→\n   377→Cloche provides containerized environments for coding agents, a workflow DSL\n   378→for linking agentic and script-driven tasks, and validated code pipelines.\n   379→\n   380→Usage:\n   381→  cloche <command> [args]\n   382→  cloche help <command>       Show detailed help for a command\n   383→  cloche <command> --help     Same as above\n   384→\n   385→Project Setup:\n   386→  init       Initialize a Cloche project (.cloche/ directory and templates)\n   387→  health     Show project health summary (pass/fail counts)\n   388→\n   389→Workflow Info:\n   390→  workflow   List workflows or show a workflow as an ASCII-art graph\n   391→\n   392→Workflow Runs:\n   393→  run        Launch a workflow run in a container\n   394→  status     Check run status (state, steps, errors)\n   395→  logs       Show or stream logs for a run\n   396→  poll       Wait for a run to finish (blocks until terminal state)\n   397→  list       List runs for current project (or all projects)\n   398→  stop       Stop a running workflow\n   399→  delete     Delete a retained container\n   400→\n   401→Orchestration:\n   402→  tasks      Show task pipeline and assignment state\n   403→  loop       Start or stop the orchestration loop\n   404→\n   405→Context Store (for use inside workflow steps):\n   406→  get        Get a value from the run context store\n   407→  set        Set a value in the run context store\n   408→\n   409→Daemon:\n   410→  shutdown   Shut down the Cloche daemon\n   411→\n   412→Environment Variables:\n   413→  CLOCHE_ADDR          Daemon gRPC address (default: unix:///tmp/cloche.sock)\n   414→  CLOCHE_HTTP          Daemon HTTP address (for health/tasks commands)\n   415→  CLOCHE_RUN_ID        Run ID for get/set commands (set automatically in steps)\n   416→  CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR   Project directory override for get/set commands\n   417→\n   418→Examples:\n   419→  cloche init\n   420→  cloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add user authentication\"\n   421→  cloche status abc123\n   422→  cloche logs abc123 --follow\n   423→  cloche list\n   424→  cloche loop --max 2\n   425→`)\n   426→}\n   427→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01R6FyHX8ezBGpk4fQZXf4qj","session_id":"c0b250b2-f9c5-4d6e-a2b5-21933ebd9c8c","uuid":"6abd3da6-9283-44d2-b202-9e9e9a3df251"}
